<DOCNO> AP880801-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
with a few minutes to spare in a long 
campaign day michael dukakis stopped by the harmony early learning 
center to shake a few hands with preschoolers 
looking to campaign on a tight preconvention budget george bush 
a day later rode out to tysons corner va in the washington 
suburbs to do the same thing tossing a foam ball and pushing 
youngsters on a tire swing 
for both it was time well spent dukakis was rewarded with 
prominent photographs in newspapers and the television networks 
and bush reaped similar coverage 
the twin events on the presidential campaign trail last week 
underscored what already has become apparent to both campaigns 
child care is a hot issue in the 1988 race for the white house 
its politics dictated by demographics the census bureau says 
more than half of new mothers go back to work before their children 
are a year old 
neither party wants to find itself outmaneuvered on the issue 
dukakis the democratic nominee and bush who will become the 
republican nominee in less than three weeks have introduced 
competing proposals on day care 
the proposals reflect their differing philosophies on government 
involvement yet importantly both candidates support in principle 
some form of government initiatives to assist parents in providing 
care for their young children 
we can ignore the fact that most women with small children now 
hold jobs or we can work to make quality affordable child care 
available to every family that needs it dukakis said 
you have to have choice parental choice family choice and 
you have to have diversity bush said 
the vice presidents plan is basically a 1000perchild tax 
break for lowincome parents of children 4 and under 
it would cost an estimated 22 billion a year and in its first 
stages would benefit only families earning less than 12000 a 
year according to bush domestic affairs adviser deborah steelman 
eventually families earning up to 20000 would benefit 
bushs plan generally would exclude the middleclass families 
that pay 100 a week or so to put a child in the centers the two 
presidential candidates visited last week in new jersey and 
virginia 
dukakis plan according to his aides largely is embodied in 
legislation now before congress that is similar to day care 
assistance being provided in his own state of massachusetts it is 
aimed at helping low and moderateincome families afford child 
care and would reserve 75 percent of its money for that aid 
states could use the rest to encourage developing and upgrading 
centers through grants it would establish standards for care and 
states would have to match a portion of the federal money 
it isnt just that day care isnt affordable its that it 
isnt available said dukakis aide victoria rideout 
the legislation would cost an estimated 25 billion but 
dukakis has stopped short of committing himself to paying that full 
amount instead saying that would be only a goal 
until i walk into the office and take a good hard look at the 
books its impossible to put an exact dollar figure on it he 
said 
dukakis aides fault the bush plan because it provides money with 
the filing of tax returns not when money is spent paying day care 
bills 
dukakis also objects to permitting the tax credit for all who 
are eligible even if the family keeps the child at home and he 
says bush would pile a tax break on top of his proposed cut in 
capital gains 
bush contends however that offering the tax break to all 
families who qualify would help parents who chose to have one 
spouse stay at home 
i am absolutely convinced he problem is so big and so diverse 
that the federal government alone cannot have a bricks and mortar 
child care program thats going to be effective bush said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
michael dukakis has drawn some large 
crowds in the two campaign swings hes taken since leaving atlanta 
as the democratic presidential nominee invariably he has 
attracted protesters too 
at virtually every stop in his campaign travels dukakis has 
been confronted by demonstrators sometimes numbering no more than 
a dozen but always vocal most carry signs and chant slogans 
objecting to the right of women to have abortions 
often mixed with them are signs supporting republican george 
bush and there are occasional signs attacking dukakis record in 
massachusetts such as the one in sturtevant wis last week that 
said michael dukakis the criminals choice go home it 
referred to the program since modified allowing prison furloughs 
for some convicted murderers in massachusetts 
the presence of antiabortion protesters recalls the campaign in 
1984 of vice presidential nominee geraldine ferraro who faced 
similar demonstrations at many speeches dukakis campaign staffers 
many of whom are veterans of the mondaleferraro effort say they 
and their candidate are not bothered or surprised by the protesters 
we expect them at every event said jim steinberg dukakis 
senior issues adviser who travels with the candidate 
the largest gathering numbering 100 or more confronted dukakis 
as he went to church on sunday a week ago in st louis in 
secaucus nj last week the dozen or so protesters positioned 
themselves so close behind the stage that their chants were picked 
up by the public address system and dukakis had to walk right by 
them as he left 
in sturtevant a day later a larger group chanted slogans 
throughout his speech and dukakis appeared to have been put off 
his stride by the distraction 
was he rattled 
rattled i didnt feel rattled did i look rattled i didnt 
feel rattled did i look rattled terribly rattled 
let me tell you if you went through the kind of governorship 
i went through in the first four years as governor of 
massachusetts thats a day at the beach added dukakis he was 
turned out of office after that turbulent first term in 1978 then 
regained it four years later 
