<DOCNO> AP880801-0035 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new president should move quickly to fill 
foreign policy posts and make clear immediately that his secretary 
of state is his one principal lieutenant in foreign affairs a 
report on presidential transition recommends 
the report noted that presidents nixon carter and reagan all 
found their administrations involved early in internal disputes 
between the national security adviser and the state department 
the report never mentioned the irancontra affair which came to 
light in president reagans second term but it said recent 
events have demonstrated the need for a new president to tell his 
national security adviser at the start precisely what role and 
responsibilities he and his staff should assume including 
their relations with the secretary of state 
coherence and consistency in foreign policy are best served if 
the president has only one principal lieutenant in that area the 
secretary of state 
the report entitled transferring responsibility the dangers 
of transition was released by the white burkett miller center of 
public affairs at the university of virginia 
the study was the work of a commission on presidential 
transitions and foreign policy headed by former secretaries of 
state cyrus r vance and william p rogers 
the commission included members of every postwar presidential 
transition from the franklin d rooseveltharry truman changeover 
to that of jimmy carter and ronald reagan 
the rogersvance commission recommended 
key foreign policy officials should be selected promptly by a 
new administration with cabinet officers chosen within four weeks 
of the election and subcabinet positions filled within 10 weeks 
the process often takes longer the report said because of 
political considerations in the white house and the senate 
key presidential foreign policy documents should be reproduced 
for the incoming president we know of no large institution other 
than the white house in which when a change of leadership occurs 
many of the files relevant to continuing policy decisions are 
packed up and taken away by the departing top official the 
report said 
the office of management and budget should be restored as the 
institutional memory of the presidents office and the number 
of political appointees at the top of omb should be reduced 
preinaugural meetings between representatives of the incoming 
administration and foreign diplomats and leaders should be sharply 
limited 
each presidential candidate should begin building a pool of 
potential foreign policy appointees immediately after the political 
party conventions and use small task forces rather than large 
transition teams 
the report said that during a presidential campaign candidates 
should be careful in the number and scope of promises they make 
in the foreign policy field some political promises which bring 
success in the election may produce failure in office 
once in office a new president should be careful not to 
politicize the career services the report said 
new administrations are often distrustful of bureaucrats and 
only slowly do they learn how heavily they can rely on the 
professionalism of foreign service officers and members of the 
other career services the report said 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

