<TEXT>
a pack of runners darted through the 
woods bushwhacked up and down thicketchoked slopes dashed along 
railroad tracks and abandoned roads forded kneedeep streams and 
slogged through thighhigh mud 
they closed out the day with beer a barbecue and good 
fellowship 
born in the rubber plantations and jungles of east asia in an 
era when the sun never set on the british empire the sport known 
as hashing has made its way halfway around the world to maine 
where one devotee is writing a book about it 
hashing a noncompetitive form of crosscountry running that 
traces its roots to the game of hare and hounds is enjoyed by 
roughly 50000 participants in more than 700 clubs in 124 countries 
from andorra to zimbabwe 
its a way to get a little exercise and a little 
sociability said freelance writer alice johnson of hallowell 
founder of the hallowell hash house harriers one of about 80 clubs 
in the united states 
california leads with 16 
for her research on her forthcoming book johnson was recently 
in bali site of the 1988 interhash known as the biennial olympics 
of hashing and in malaysia for the the 50th anniversary 
celebration of the founding of the original hash house harriers 
known affectionately as the mother hash 
the group was founded at a kuala lumpur club by british soldiers 
and expatriate businessmen who ran through the jungle to work up a 
thirst it selected the name from the institutional quality of the 
clubs food 
at a midsummer hash that began at her lakefront cottage here 
johnson briefed newcomers on the rules runners designated as hares 
set the course in advance marking it with flour they are the only 
ones who know where it will lead 
at various points hares draw circles indicating checkpoints 
from which several possible routes fan out in different directions 
all but one are false trails that end with a marker telling the 
runner to return to the checkpoint and try again 
the runner who finally discovers the right trail shouts im 
on or onon the hares who follow the pack to keep track of 
stragglers sound a horn and all run toward the next checkpoint to 
restart the process 
the search for the correct trail provides time for slower 
runners to catch up with those up front 
it takes away a lot of the ego trip involved with track and 
other competitive racing said noel mount an irishborn former 
rugby player who was one of the two dozen hallowell hashers to run 
the nearly sixmile course 
you get ahead but then you take the wrong trail and that 
brings you back with everyone else 
johnsons husband wick along with summer neighbors oliver 
greeves and andrew engelman reconnoitered the area the previous 
evening and spent three hours that morning laying out the route and 
marking it with 10 pounds of flour in the tropics hares use paper 
rather than flour to leave their marks 
greeves a resident of hong kong introduced the johnsons to 
hashing two years ago while on a visit to hong kong wick johnson 
was invited by greeves to participate in an allmale hash he 
returned exhausted but enthusiastic telling his wife a 
recreational runner that this was a sport she would love 
upon her return home that summer alice johnson rounded up a 
group of friends and neighbors from hallowell just outside 
augusta and organized the areas first hash 
the trick is getting the right people at the beginning it has 
to be people who dont take themselves too seriously she said 
most are runners but it is definitely not a requirement you 
just have to be fit enough to run approximately six miles with 
stops 
</TEXT>
