<TEXT>
this old us 
navy mine sweeper and five others like it may remain in the persian 
gulf until an estimated couple of hundred mines still lurking 
in the waters are found and destroyed us officers say 
while a ceasefire in the iraqiran war would probably keep new 
mines from being laid those already deployed could pose a danger 
to shipping for years to come unless cleaned up 
the task falls to ships like the creaky 800ton conquest whose 
crew works these days in 130degree deck temperatures using a 
submersible robot to locate mines and trailing gear to cut the 
cables that moor them to the seabed 
when a submerged mine shows up on the sonar screen divers are 
guided to the spot and attach explosives which are detonated by 
time fuse or remote control 
capt jim miller commodore of the us minesweeping force 
would not predict how long the tedious and dangerous job of 
clearing the gulf of mines might require 
were not going to do it in a week or two weeks he said in 
an interview its going to take a lot longer than that 
miller said this could mean some or all of the six us mine 
sweepers in the gulf might be excluded from a force cutback 
promised by us officials when and if tehran and baghdad formally 
agree to a truce in their 8yearold war 
iran which is blamed for laying most of the mines in the gulf 
announced july 18 that it would join iraq in accepting a yearold 
un ceasefire resolution 
the woodenhulled us mine sweepers all built in the early 
1950s but updated for gulf duty with modern sonar navigation and 
minehunting gear comprise about a third of the us naval force 
now in the gulf 
their mothership is the amphibious landing ship dubuque 
which also carries about 400 marines and eight helicopters 
us military sources in washington say the six aging mine 
sweepers might possibly be given to a gulf arab state rather than 
returned to the united states the navy has 15 other mine sweepers 
of similar vintage and is building 31 new stateoftheart ships 
for hunting mines 
miller said he had no firsthand knowledge of such a plan 
but noted that scores of former us warships are now sailing with 
other navies 
he conceded it could take years before the gulf is free of 
mines if ever mines laid in the north sea during world war ii 
were still being recovered as recently as 1980 he said 
the mine threat had a major role in prompting the naval buildup 
by the united states and five european navies in the gulf a year 
ago 
in addition to the six us craft which arrived in november 
britain france italy belgium and the netherlands sent antimine 
forces the soviet union also has ships capable of minesweeping in 
the waterway 
european forces were later cut back and two remaining belgian 
and dutch minehunters combined with three british ships under 
royal navy command 
us navy records indicate at least 10 vessels have hit mines in 
the gulf since the soviet tanker marshal chuikov was damaged off 
kuwait on may 16 1987 
among later victims were the usflagged kuwaiti supertanker 
bridgeton the american frigate samuel b roberts an offshore 
supply vessel sunk with six killed and an ocean survey ship with 
four lost 
after the samuel b roberts narrowly escaped destruction in the 
central gulf on april 14 us searchers found three more mines in 
those waters 
officers said all were clean of marine growth indicating they 
were newly laid and one bore the letters usa in white paint 
the mines of a 1908 russian type were identical with those 
found aboard the captured iranian minelayer iran ajr in september 
they said 
overall some 80 mines have been found in the past year 
according to available records 
miller said everybody has found some the us navy found 
52 the latest in may the british and french each have found more 
than a dozen 
miller said the estimated couple of hundred mines still in 
the gulf are concentrated in certain areas including waters just 
south of iraq and an area of the northern gulf near iranianheld 
farsi island 
the mines off iraq believed laid by both sides are a special 
threat because they break lose in rough weather and drift to the 
arab side of the gulf several vessels have struck these renegade 
floaters off kuwait saudi arabia and bahrain 
