<TEXT>
the chinese military celebrated its 61st 
anniversary today by restoring a ranking system in a move seen as 
critical to its efforts to develop a modern fighting force 
in related developments saturday the peoples liberation army 
bestowed medals on thousands of veterans and announced more than 
100000 soldiers would be transferred to a new civilian staff 
western military analysts in beijing and the official chinese 
media said the moves were connected to reforms aimed at modernizing 
chinas armed forces and ridding it of the leftist influences 
the analysts who spoke on condition of anonymity also said the 
ranking system was designed to raise the morale of the army which 
since 1978 has seen many of its factories converted to civilian use 
and its troop strength and share of the state budget slashed 
mao tsetung abolished military ranks 23 years ago as part of 
his attempt to create a classless society china then ascribed to a 
fighting philosophy called peoples war which envisaged an 
allout war fought by a huge peasant army 
since china began its economic reforms in 1978 it has moved to 
create a professional army with topnotch military equipment 
western analysts today said chinas poor showing in its brief 
war with vietnam in 1979 also did much to convince military leaders 
of the necessity of a strict ranking system 
in addition the trouble with vietnam on the border and over 
islands in the south pacific has led the chinese to believe future 
conflicts will not be an allout war but geographically contained 
battles that necessitate a rapid deployment force of highly trained 
soldiers said one diplomat 
these kinds of units need a strict command structure with a 
clear delineation as to who is giving and who is receiving the 
orders he said before today they didnt have that 
fridays issue of the peoples daily renmin ribao said the 
move to transfer 100000 soldiers to civilian status was part of a 
program to cut the number of officials in the army 
the ratio of officials to soldiers is lopsided it said 
they are too many officers and many of them are too old 
apart from strategic issues analysts said the ranking system 
and the awarding of medals were undertaken to raise morale in the 
peoples liberation army 
since 1978 china had reduced the army from 4 million to 3 
million men cut the armys share of the state budget from 175 
percent to less than 10 percent and turned military industry 
factories to consumer production 
in addition the army has all but been shut out of politics 
finally a program to acquire advanced weapons systems has been 
slowed because of budget constraints 
if the army is not getting weapons the least the government 
can give them is ranks said one analyst 
analysts said china had to award medals and ranks to its 
veterans some of whom maintain a strong influence over the 
military because it would have been an insult to award ranks only 
to those currently in service 
part of the reason all this took so long is that the veterans 
were bickering about who was to get which medal or which rank 
one analyst said citing chinese sources they are evidently very 
concerned with status 
