construction spending edged up 01 percent in 
june as continued strength in nonresidential building offset 
declines in housing and government projects the government said 
today 
the commerce department said building activity rose to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4028 billion in june 
following a 08 percent increase in may in april construction 
plunged 11 percent after soaring 28 percent in march the june 
level was 26 percent higher than a year ago 
the strength came from a 25 percent increase in spending on 
nonresidential construction which climbed to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 992 billion led by big jumps in both 
factory and hotelmotel construction it was the fourth consecutive 
monthly increase 
factory construction rose 57 percent and now stands 21 percent 
higher than it was a year ago us manufacturers have boosted 
investment on new factories because of a surge in export sales 
caused by the weaker dollar 
hotel and motel construction increased 194 percent after 
falling for two months 
construction of office buildings in june was off by 04 percent 
from the may level however the small decline followed increases 
in may april and march and the june rate was still 12 percent 
higher than a year ago something of a puzzle to analysts because 
of lingering high vacancy rates in that sector caused by widespread 
overbuilding in previous years 
residential construction fell 09 percent in june to an annual 
rate of 1881 billion the third decline in a row that sector has 
been hurt by an increase in mortgage interest rates since the 
spring a 07 percent drop in construction of singlefamily homes 
more than offset a 23 percent increase in apartment construction 
government construction projects fell 14 percent in june to an 
annual rate of 786 billion with highway construction the biggest 
segment of the government sector suffering a 16 percent decline 
