<TEXT>
four soviet missiles were blown apart today at a 
test range on the steppes of central asia as the soviet union began 
destroying more than 1700 missiles banned by a superpower treaty 
tass said 
defense secretary frank carlucci who today arrived for a 
fourday visit to the soviet union hailed the destruction of the 
missiles as a great event 
tass said that at noon moscow time four soviet shortrange 
missiles known in the west as ss12s were destroyed in the presence 
of us inspectors at the saryozek test range in soviet kazakhstan 
about 1800 miles southeast of moscow 
western reporters watched from a distance of about two miles as 
a single explosion tore apart the four missiles 
the blast dug a crater about 65 feet wide and spread debris 
from the missiles over several hundred yards they said the 
explosion sent a huge cloud of smoke into the blue sky over the 
steppe the western reporters said 
col stanislav petrenko chief of operations told reporters the 
nuclear warheads mounted on the ss12s had been removed before the 
rockets were destroyed and that the charges would be used for 
peaceful purposes 
the soviet union has used nuclear explosions for oil 
prospecting largescale construction projects and other purposes 
petrenko told western reporters that an explosion would take 
place at the saryozek site every day for the next 18 months tass 
the official soviet news agency said other soviet missiles banned 
by the superpower treaty would be destroyed over the next three 
years 
the superpowers signed a treaty in december banning their 
medium and shorterrange nuclear missiles it is the first arms 
agreement between the two nations that calls for the destruction of 
an entire class of weaponry 
under the treaty the soviets must eliminate 1752 missiles with 
a range of between 310 miles and 3410 miles that have been 
deployed or are in storage tass said 
the united states has said it will scrap 859 pershing 2 and 
cruise missiles now stationed in western europe 
the intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty signed by 
president reagan and soviet communist party general secretary 
mikhail s gorbachev calls for each country to allow inspectors 
from the other side to verify that the rockets have been eliminated 
on april 11 the soviet union said it blew up six ss12 missiles 
in a test designed to develop a method to destroy missiles under 
the treaty the united states also conducted such tests 
carlucci when asked by reporters how he evaluated the 
destruction of the missiles said i think its a great event 
im very pleased to see it 
his host soviet defense minister dmitri t yazov added it 
means that we are starting to carry out the obligations which were 
achieved earlier especially as a result of the four summit 
meetings in geneva reykjavik washington and moscow 
tass said the destruction of the missiles will lead to a 
substantial lowering of the level of military confrontation in 
europe and to the lessening of the risk of global nuclear 
conflict 
