<TEXT>
iraq is continuing to use mustard and 
nerve gas on an intensive scale in its eightyear war with iran 
despite frequent pleas that it cease according to a report by a 
team of un experts released today 
the secretarygeneral cannot but express his deep regret at 
the missions conclusion that chemical weapons continue to be used 
against iranian forces and positions un chief javier perez de 
cuellar said in a statement 
there was no immediate reaction from iraq and the iraqi mission 
said officials were not available foreign minister tariq aziz of 
iraq in new york for un talks on ending the iraniraq war last 
month acknowledged that iraqi soldiers used chemical weapons 
ambassador mohammad jaafar mahallati of iran said today that 
the report only refers to allegations against iran only cites 
nine soldiers 
he added he hoped the report will only further motivate the 
security council to exert all pressure and leverage against iraq to 
accept a ceasefire and comprehensive settlement 
the secretarygeneral is conducting talks with both sides on 
ending their war and implementing a ceasefire 
the un inquiry was requested by iran which charged that iraq 
had used the weapons frequently and on a massive scale killing 
thousands of people in the spring at iraqs request the team 
later went to baghdad 
the team said it examined iraqi soldiers who had been injured by 
mustard gas but did not conclude that iran used chemical weapons 
earlier un reports also have documented use of the weapons by 
iraq and the baghdad government has admitted using chemical 
weapons iranian officials had denied using the weapons 
the danger of continuing escalation involving the use of those 
weapons of mass destruction in violation of the geneva protocol 
and in spite of repeated findings and numerous appeals is a 
frightening possibility which must be fully faced by all concerned 
and the international community as a whole the 
secretarygenerals statement said 
in may the security council condemned the increasing use of 
chemical weapons in the iraniraq war and urged restraint by both 
sides 
we deeply regret to say that in spite of repeated appeals 
by the united nations chemical weapons continue to be used on an 
intensive scale against iranian forces the report by chemical 
warfare specialists said 
the 53page report consists of two parts based on visits to both 
iran and iraq at the requests of the two government 
it said clinical examinations of nine iraqi soldiers showed 
their injuries had been produced by mustard gas the iraqis 
displayed mortar grenades that showed evidence of mustard gas and 
said they had been used by the iranians the team said 
the section on iraqs use of the weapons is more detailed 
involving more patients and locations and studies of chemical bomb 
fragments the report describes numerous injuries caused by mustard 
gas but said the investigators could not confirm reports of nerve 
gas use because it disappears quickly 
the medical chief and others in an iranian war zone told the 
investigators that because it dissipates quickly and allows 
attackers to advance the nerve gas was used against front line 
troops they said mustard gas was used against rear areas to 
disrupt possible counterattacks because of its lasting effects 
the team visited iran from july 1 to 5 went to hospitals in 
bakhtaran and ahvas and traveled to the war zone in the southwest 
it visited iraq on july 10 and 11 and visited hospitals in as 
sulaymaniyah and baghdad 
the team consisted of two chemical weapons specialists dr erik 
dahlgren of the swedish defense research institute in umea sweden 
