<TEXT>
a witness said monday hundreds of 
people were standing on a section of ferry pier when it collapsed 
onto a ramp packed with cars and motorcycles killing at least 31 
people and injuring more than 800 
cheong ah chye 21 was one of thousands waiting to board the 
ferry sunday evening to attend a chinese religious festival on 
penang island about three miles away and said he was only about a 
yard from the section that collapsed 
the ferry has an upper deck for passengers and a lower level for 
cars trucks and motorcycles 
s naga rajan a journalist for the daily star of penang said 
he had stepped onto the ferry only seconds before the disaster he 
said hundreds of people had jammed the boarding area of the pier 
justling and clambering over barriers 
rajan said i had just stepped onto the ferry when i heard a 
loud noise i turned around and saw that the portion from the 
beginning of the pathway to the ferry and the area around the 
sliding gate had fallen 
i rushed down to the vehicle section of the ferry and saw that 
the whole platform around the area iron beams planks and wires 
had collapsed with the people on it it fell on vehicles on the 
lower floor going into the ferry 
then i saw people bleeding in the head face arms and legs 
emerging from the debris many were covered with dirt and all were 
in shock 
some mothers their faces bleeding were looking for their 
children some people were crying others offered prayers a number 
of people were trapped under the iron beams and debris soon police 
and firemen arrived to pull them out 
mohamed noorani kamarun deputy secretary of penang state and 
head of the rescue operation told reporters monday that earlier 
reports of 35 dead were wrong he said 31 people had been killed 
including 13 who died in hospitals 
he said only three of the casualties had been found to be 
foreigners two from singapore and a french tourist with minor 
injuries 
prime minister mahathir mohamad flew to butterworth from kuala 
lumpur the capital city 180 miles to the southeast and visited 
the injured at a government hospital 
mahathir said an immediate payment of about 800 would be made 
to the family of each of the dead and other compensation might be 
provided 
rescue officials said most of the debris had been cleared away 
and no more bodies or survivors were expected to be found 
butterworth has two ferry piers the one remaining intact 
resumed operation monday after a safety inspection 
only passengers were allowed on the pier vehicles were ordered 
to use the bridge that links this port of 50000 people to penang 
island across the strait of malacca 
the rescue center said all but two of the dead had been 
indentified and the total number injured was 863 including 417 
still hospitalized 
