<TEXT>
following are key dates in the continued postponement of the 
space shuttle flight 
jan 28 1986 space shuttle challenger blows up shortly after 
launch killing crew of seven 
may 15 1986 arnold aldrich manager of the shuttle system 
tells congressional committee that target date for next launch of 
discovery is july 15 1987 
oct 3 1986 nasa announces target date of feb 18 1988 for 
discovery launch 
jan 14 1987 national research council reports that nasa will 
not have time to evaluate or incorporate any safety changes if it 
attempts to meet feb 18 1988 launch target 
april 21 1987 nasa announces it cannot meet feb 18 1988 
date and slates additional tests no new target announced 
june 2 1987 rear adm richard truly says that discovery will 
be launched june 2 1988 if all tests go according to schedule 
nov 23 1987 national research council recommends additional 
testing of solidfuel engine which might require postponing june 
launch 
dec 29 1987 nasa announces that june launch date has been 
postponed because of failure of booster rocket nozzle during a 
test nasa officials say launch date will be moved back 610 weeks 
jan 11 1988 nasa administrator james c fletcher says launch 
will be between midjuly and midaugust of 1988 
jan 27 1988 nasa sets aug 4 as launch date 
april 26 1988 shuttle manbager arnold aldrich says launch 
will be pushed back at least until aug 14 because of unexpected 
delays in assembling redesigned booster rockets 
may 4 1988 fletcher says aug 25 is a possible launch date 
although it might be early september nasa subsequently selects 
aug 31 date 
june 10 1988 the external fuel tank is joined to the solid 
rocket boosters and astronaut bob crippen deputy director of 
shuttle operations says weve got a shot at meeting the aug 
31 target test firing of shuttles liquidfuel engines is set for 
july 18 
july 15 1988 discovery sprang a small gas leak in one of its 
steering engines and nasa said there was a possibility of 
additional delay in the launch now set for sept 3 
july 22 1988 nasa announce twoday delay in test firing of 
main engines which had been planned for july 30 
july 29 1988 nasa postpones test firing again setting date 
of aug 4 after discovering leak in a hydrogen line during fueling 
aug 1 1988 another hydrogen leak is detected but nasa goes 
ahead with the countdown rehearsal no decision on whether to 
postpone the testfiring will be made until tuesday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

