<TEXT>
china on monday brought back military ranks to 
its army in a move to modernize its fighting force and boost morale 
after years of personnel cuts and tight budgets 
the move came on the 61st anniversary of the peoples liberation 
army and 23 years after mao tsetung banned ranks as inappropriate 
to his classless peasant army 
on oct 1 chinas national day soldiers are to don new 
uniforms with insignia designating their military positions 
the government also issued regulations spelling out awards to be 
given to servicemen and their families so as to encourage their 
dedicated spirit in defending and building the motherland 
the new regulations guarantee servicemen that they will not lose 
their farmland when they are conscripted as well offer pensions to 
those disabled in combat and pay damages to the families of those 
who died in combat 
on saturday communist party secretary general zhao ziyang and 
other senior leaders gathered at the great hall of the people to 
bestow medals on more than 80000 veterans 
western military analysts in beijing who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the ranking system was designed to raise the morale 
of the army after troop strength and state funding were slashed in 
the past decade and many military factories were converted to 
civilian use 
the analysts said a need for reinstating ranks became evident 
after the chinese armys embarrassing showing in a brief 1979 
border war with vietnam 
these kinds of units need a strict command structure with a 
clear delineation as to who is giving and who is receiving the 
orders said a diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity 
before today they didnt have that 
the analysts said mondays move is also aimed at ridding the 
army of leftist influences 
in 1965 mao abolished military ranks as part of his attempt to 
create a radically egalitarian society in which a massive peasant 
army would would be called on to fight a peoples war 
deng xiaoping who rose to power in 1978 has rejected maos 
concept and has tried to create a professional army today 70 
percent of military commanders have college educations compared to 
16 percent in 1982 
deng who controls the military as head of the central military 
commission has reduced the size of chinas armed forces to 3 
million from 4 million in 1985 and has introduced modern 
technology 
he has also shaved the militarys share of the government budget 
from 175 percent in 1978 to less than 10 percent 
deng has also supported the transfer of cadres or officers 
to civilian duty as part of an effort to cut the oversized corps 
many of whom were either aging or poorly trained 
among the 1 million soldiers demobilized in the past few years 
450000 were cadres the government announced that an additional 
100000 officers would be transferred to a civilian staff of 
educators and specialists 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

