<TEXT>
the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution 
bucking recent trends in newspaper style have restored the use of 
courtesy titles for men and women in their news columns 
under the new rules the first reference to individuals will 
include full proper names along with the use of public military 
professional and ecclesiastical titles the newspapers said in a 
frontpage note announcing the policy in their combined editions 
sunday 
on second reference names will be preceded by the earned 
title or the courtesy title for all individuals and not just for 
women as is now the case 
for example when the newspaper writes about the citys top 
elected official it will be mayor andrew young on first reference 
and mayor young on subsequent references or in stories about one 
of the citys top businessmen it will be ted turner followed by 
mr turner 
the decision is in contrast to many newspapers which have moved 
closer to dropping courtesy titles such as mr mrs miss or ms 
only a few newspapers notably the new york times and the wall 
street journal use the courtesy title mr 
for some time we have been troubled by the limited use of 
courtesy titles in our news columns editor bill kovach said in 
the frontpage note 
we hope the sense of dignity and respect that the consistent 
use of courtesy titles implies will more adequately reflect the 
relationship we believe exists between us and our readers said 
kovach who came to the newspapers from the new york times 
washington bureau 
the newspapers left unchanged their policy for sports stories 
which do not include courtesy titles for men or women 
