<TEXT>
a federal judge has ordered the government to 
change or delete unconstitutionally vague language in pledges 
signed by 17 million government workers not to disclose topsecret 
information 
us district judge oliver gasch ordered the modification in the 
nondisclosure pledges signed by government workers with access to 
topsecret information must sign to retain their security 
clearances 
in an order signed friday and made public monday the judge said 
the government must provide a more specific definition of the term 
classifiable information 
in signing the various pledges government employees promise not 
to make unauthorized disclosures of topsecret information or 
classifiable information 
gasch gave the information security oversight office 60 days to 
notify the federal employees of the governments definition or 
classifiable information or to declare the term inoperative 
until that notification is made the government cannot penalize 
employees who disclose classifiable information the judge said 
a more specific definition must also be included in forms 
presented to federal employees who have not yet signed the pledge 
or the term must be deleted the judge said 
the ruling was made in a lawsuit by two federal employees unions 
that contended the pledges use throughout the executive branch 
empowered government agencies to penalize whistleblowers by 
classifying information after it was disclosed to the press or 
members of congress 
gasch suggested that the security agency headed by steven 
garfinkel could adopt a definition published late last year in the 
federal register 
that regulation defined classifiable information as any 
unstamped material or oral conversations that an employee has a 
good reason to know should be classified 
such information would include material that was in the process 
of being reviewed for classification according to the regulatory 
definition published dec 21 1987 
gasch upheld the validity of that definition saying much 
classified information is not marked as such because it has not 
been examined by a classification authority the govenrment 
nevertheless has a substantial interest in safeguarding that 
information 
the 1987 definition simply requires that employees consider 
whether they have reason to believe that unmarked information is 
classified or should be classified and is in the process of 
becoming so gasch said 
the regulation was offered to allay concerns raised by the 
plaintiffs who brought the lawsuit 
but gasch said that until an employee becomes aware of the 
regulatory definition he cannot know what classifiable 
information does not include for example information that only 
speculation suggests will become classified 
notice of the definition is essential the judge said 
the decision was hailed by both sides of the dispute 
garfinkel noted that gasch had upheld the general principle that 
federal employees can be required to sign secrecy pledges 
i think essentially its a victory for the broader principle 
it will require us to do something more as far as the forms that 
hae already been signed is concerned garfinkel said we will 
have to decide which option to take 
patti goldman an attorney for public citizen litigation group 
a consumer lobby that filed a friendofthecourt brief for several 
members of congress said the order teaches a lesson to the 
government that they have to be more careful when they are crafting 
these agreements 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

