<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency said 
monday it wants the government to capture expected windfall 
corporate profits that could reach 7 billion during future cuts in 
production of chemicals that destroy the earths protective ozone 
layer 
but the agency said it had not decided how to do that and one 
major producer said it doubts that there will be major windfalls as 
the chemicals chlorofluorocarbon or cfc compounds are cut back 
under epas expectations the shortage of cfc compounds will 
enable producers to raise prices with no increase in production 
costs 
epa disclosed that it was considering regulations that could 
require manufacturers to pay fees to the government equal to their 
extra profits could require recycling or other controls on 
manufacturing processes or could require companies to buy 
manufacturing rights from the government at auctions open to anyone 
the agency announced final adoption of detailed regulations 
including production quotas to carry out last years treaty 
obliging major nations to cut cfc production 50 percent by 1998 
epa expects enough countries to ratify the treaty for it to take 
effect next jan 1 eleven nations accounting for twothirds of 
world production must ratify six including the united states have 
done so 
eileen claussen acting deputy epa administrator for air 
programs said the agency leans toward fees perhaps supplemented 
by direct controls as a way of capturing windfall profits the 
presidents office of management and budget on the other hand 
favors auctioning the production rights 
epas authority to proceed without legislation is cloudy ms 
claussen said 
an auction she said could be administratively unworkable if 
10000 small companies participate if it was judged to be 
illegal we would have nothing we wouldnt be in compliance with 
the montreal protocol she said 
and she said theres a lot of concern about hoarding in 
which large companies like auto manufacturers would keep smaller 
concerns such as those making plastic foams for furniture 
cushions from getting production rights 
epa wants to the government to get the increased profits because 
our concern is the incentive producers might have for keeping an 
existing product in production delaying the switch to 
environmentally harmless alternatives said john hoffman project 
officer for the regulations 
the largest producer of cfcs du pont co said it believed no 
action was needed to take extra profits away from the producers 
because they would be small or nonexistent 
one producer after another is announcing progress with 
substitutes said joe steed environmental manager for cfcs for 
du pont substitution is the driving force were going to see 
if we can fund development at the rate we think we need well be 
doing well 
epa said the increase in profits over the 1986 level could range 
from 18 billion if user companies rapidly find alternatives to 
72 billion if cfc compounds are kept on the market as long as 
possible 
the montreal treaty binds participating countries to a reduction 
of 20 percent in cfc production in 1993 and a further 30 percent 
cut in 1998 all calculated from a 1986 base 
the longlived cfc compounds ascend to the ozone layer 15 to 25 
miles high where since about 1960 they have destroyed about 25 
percent of the ozone protecting humans from skin cancer from the 
suns ultraviolet rays normally blocked by ozone 
epa estimates that every percent decrease in ozone results on 
43000 additional skin cancer cases in the united states currently 
there are about 500000 cases a year 
the regulation will prevent about 37 million early deaths among 
people now alive in the united states or to be born by the year 
2075 epa estimated 
financially the impact on the consumer will be very small 
because cfc use is such a small part of the cost of production and 
large price increases will be easily absorbed even if the increase 
is five or sixfold epas hoffman said 
cfcs are widely used as refrigeration fluids solvents and 
plastic foam blowing agents they are banned as us aerosol 
propellants but still used as propellants abroad a new car 
typically contains 25 pounds of a cfc compound used as air 
conditioning fluid costing about 150 
epas regulations if triggered by the treaty going into effect 
mean that in the 12 months beginning july 1 1989 the five us 
manufacturers will be bound by these manufacturing quotas to the 
nearest million pounds du pont co 336 million pounds 
alliedsignal corp 171 million pennwalt corp 86 million 
kaiser chemicals co 62 million and racon inc 30 million 
similar quotas apply separately to the sum of production plus 
imports minus exports du pont 308 million pounds alliedsignal 
163 million pennwalt 84 million kaiser 61 million racon 30 
million and 10 companies whose imports totaled almost 13 million 
pounds 
related compounds called halons used in fire extinguishers will 
be subject to similar quotas starting in 1992 
the companies may transfer these quotas among themselves 
</TEXT>
