<TEXT>
copenhill a vinecovered slope with a nice view 
of atlanta is popular with people who cut swaths through georgia 
in 1864 gen william t sherman camped there during the battle 
for atlanta before he burned the city and began his ruinous march 
to the sea 
in the late 1960s there was a plan to build a road through the 
area and the state condemned and destroyed hundreds of homes to 
make way for it before the project was dropped 
the carter presidential center occupies it now and wants to 
build a road linking the complex to downtown atlanta but the 
rightofway sits empty and overgrown as neighborhood groups 
continue a battle over whether the road should be built 
at one point when construction started workers shook 
protesters from trees today the fight is quieter 
court action has stopped construction since mid1986 
opponents of the expresway as they call it have been in 
court for years saying the noise fumes and roadwidening would 
damage historic parks and neighborhoods including some designed by 
pioneer urban landscaper frederick law olmstead the road also 
would slice through a public golf course 
road advocates argue the road was part of the presidential 
center package that no more homes would be leveled that it is 
needed for safety reasons and would lessen traffic through the 
older neighborhoods they say the project would leave some olmstead 
parks untouched and trim two only slightly 
they note that court decisions have agreed with the need and 
with the environmental impact statements they have filed 
road opponents are awaiting word on whether the us supreme 
court will hear their appeal 
terry adamson lawyer for former president carter who also does 
work for the center said that without the road part of the carter 
center could be reclaimed because the center got the use of 27 of 
the 30 acres of the library site from the state with the 
understanding that the road would be built the argument has been 
used since the controversy began 
it wasnt true then and its not true now countered rm 
ossoff a leader of the antiroad movement 
he said elected officials from us senators to city councilmen 
are overwhelmingly in favor of the carter center but that political 
support for the road is dropping 
demonstrate to me how that much assembled influence could not 
resolve in three seconds any problems the presidential center might 
have he said 
the center already has landscaped the 27 acres at a cost of 
about 4 million 
the road was meant to facilitate access to the carter 
presidential center near downtown atlanta and when carter proposed 
the library he all but made the road a condition of the center 
being in atlanta 
opponents of the proposed 22mile presidential parkway say 
traffic through the area is short of predictions and that a 
smoothly operating carter center belies the claim that the center 
needs the road to function 
plans call for the fourlane road to have hiking trails bike 
paths and other park facilities alongside it and proponents say it 
actually will enhance the area 
olmstead designed new york citys central park the grounds of 
the us capitol the emerald necklace of parks around boston 
and washingtons rock creek park in the 1890s he designed five 
parks in atlanta 
a 1985 bill requiring the national park service to make 
recommendations for preserving olmsteads work passed the house but 
died in the senate in 1984 the federal highway commissions 
advisory council on historic preservation voted 124 against 
building the road 
yard signs flourish near the proposed road save dont 
pave stop the road and build it in plains the latter 
referring to carters hometown of plains ga 
there have been attempts to put a road through the area for 20 
years and the state condemned land and destroyed over 500 houses 
and businesses with that in mind in the late 1960s and early 1970s 
then largely because of opposition from thengov jimmy carter 
the plan died 
the initial proposal for the presidential parkway was based 
heavily on a projected traffic increase of more than 200 percent 
over 20 years but road opponents say the actual increase has been 
closer to 10 percent 
carter center officials predicted 12 million visitors a year 
would come to the center the total for the first year was about 
175000 
not one presidential library in the united states is on a 
fourlane road and there is not any reason to believe that the 
jimmy carter library is going to draw any more visitors than the 
jfk library or the lbj library opposition leader sally dorn said 
at the height of the controversy 
neighborhood citizens groups formed caution citizens against 
unnecessary thoroughfares in older neighborboods in early 1982 to 
coordinate the protest efforts 
ossoff the first president of caution says the group has spent 
more than 400000 in legal fees and that donated legal services 
have come to far more than that adamson said road proponents have 
spent at least that much 
