editors note was there ever a golden era of sports in the dim 
past as touted by septuagenarian chroniclers maybe not but 
theres one right now its the pga senior tour where golfs 
ancient rake in the lucre in postcareer careers that lack the 
pressure and cutthroat solemnity of youthful competition but make 
up for it in sheer pleasure on the back nine of life 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at times the senior scene seems lifted live from the frame of an 
old dutch golfing print the whimsical kind you still find hanging 
in country club corridors and locker rooms 
genial gentlemen of mellowing vintage in broadbrimmed hats and 
knickerbockers bent over long crooked sticks in studious pursuit of 
nudging a small white ball across a pleasant expanse of lawn or 
perhaps these are scottish shepherds who have lost their sheep in 
the highland heather 
weep no idle tennysonian tears for a vanished yesteryear these 
are here and now maturing millionaires some for the second time 
around playing the pga senior tour sports biggest success story 
in the past decade 
its a mulligan on life a chance for a second career at an 
age when all other athletes are over the hill exulted the 
australian bruce crampton who made a million on the regular tour 
retired to hunt oil in texas for eight years then returned at age 
50 to strike it rich again as a senior 
in golf a mulligan is a second drive off the first tee allowed 
in friendly circles to compensate for a dismal start but purely 
illegal even on the senior tour where the over50 set now competes 
in a friendly way for official prize money in excess of 10 million 
the lucre is so lucrative that last year no fewer than a dozen 
seniors made more than in their regular career at least a 
halfdozen more are poised to join crampton and seven other seniors 
who already have won a million on the back nine of life 
here indeed is a new golden age of sport beyond the most 
avaricious dreams of the actuarial tables 
the old sarge orville moody recently matriculated to the 
millionaire class is a splendid example of delayed golf growth 
moodys only win in 17 years on the regular tour was the us open 
in 1969 prior to that this partchoctaw indian spent l4 years in 
the army rising to the envious rank of noncom in charge of golf 
installations joining the seniors he tucked a 50inch long 
putter now affectionately known as the staff sergeant tight 
unto his sternum and began pendulum stroking putts that now 
guarantee a more generous pension than the pentagon had in mind 
in physical contour moody more resembles sgt snorkel in the 
beetle bailey comic strip than your supple super jock senior 
millionaires come in all sizes from the wellrounded billy casper 
and miller barber to lean and hungry exercise fanatics like 
crampton a daily visitor to the physical fitness van in the 
parking lot and gary player who still does 300 situps a night on 
the motel floor 
but even with the choice of riding in carts isnt it hot work 
for chaps their age to be flailing away with woods and irons across 
seven miles of uncooperating landscape for the better part of a 
week 
playing golf is not hot work demurs chi chi rodriguez 
cutting sugar cane for a dollar a day thats hot work hotter 
than my first wristwatch 
chi chi who took up golf at 25 cents a bag as a caddy in his 
native puerto rico managed to match in less than 30 months at 
senior play the million it took him 25 years to win on the regular 
tour anything is possible in america says this jovial 
ambassador of the friendly laidback brand of golf that has made 
the senior tour such a hit with the galleries and tv audiences 
instantly recognizable in his straw fedora chi chi finds time 
to chat with the fans behind the marshals ropes to autograph caps 
and sun visors and visit with kids and old people in wheelchairs 
after sinking a 20footer he goes into his duelist act wiping 
imaginary blood from his putter and seemingly sheathing it like a 
swordsman returning a sabre to its scabbard 
suddenly golf is fun again in an age when so many younger 
players come across as unsmiling monosyllabic computerprogrammed 
golfing machines abandoning the color and drama to foreign players 
like the fiery spaniard seve ballesteros australias great 
white shark greg norman and masters champion sandy lyle the 
slender scot who deepened golfs mystique by revealing that his 
girlfriend cured his tensions by tickling his feet 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

