<TEXT>
there are no sure things in bobbie ann masons 
stories just endless possibilities 
i think in terms of possibility its part of my heritage 
said mason whose second novel is called spence lila harper 
and row 1295 
spence and lila culpepper are a couple in their 60s who live on 
a farm in western kentucky they are brought together with their 
three children nancy catherine and lee when lila is diagnosed as 
having breast cancer and must undergo surgery 
mason a native of western kentucky contrasts the lives of 
spence and lila who have spent most of their lives on the farm to 
those of the children who have moved away 
its a very confusing time for people of that the childrens 
generation the author said theyre subject to so many 
influences and problems because of all the choices they can get 
divorced their parents couldnt do that so many influences so 
much more money 
while the children move around the country trying to find 
themselves spence is perfectly happy to stay on the farm 
theres a passage where spence is looking around the farm and 
thinking that everyone is breaking their necks trying to get 
something grand mason said for spence its right here on 
the farm the basic facts of the universe are here birth growth 
and death 
it is extraordinary to plant soy beans and harvest them 
mason born in 1940 can relate well to the culpepper children 
she grew up on a dairy farm near mayfield ky and was the first 
member of her family to go college taking journalism classes at 
the university of kentucky 
she has also done her share of moving after college she lived 
in new york and went to graduate school at the state university in 
binghamton ny and the uny 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ty of connecticut she now lives 
with her husband in rural pennsylvania 
masons independence and thirst for adventure was inspired by 
the movies her parents took her to see as a child 
they saw movies but they didnt have the sense that they 
could just take off and go to california and go where the movies 
are she said it seemed possible for me to go out there 
the radio also had an impact on the author 
i first listened to rhythm and blues in the late 40s and 
early 50s mason recalled that struck a very deep chord in me 
one of those formative things i certainly had the longing and 
curiosity and wanting to experience new things 
thats why i have spence as a rock n roll fan 
masons first story was published in 1980 two years later she 
released shiloh a collection of short stories that won the 
penernest hemingway award for first fiction 
in 1985 she came out with her first novel in country the 
story of sam hughes a teenager trying to learn more about her 
late father a vietnam soldier killed before she was born 
in country was a best seller a film adaptation starring 
the english actress emily lloyd as sam and bruce willis as her 
uncle is in progess 
mason writes sparely leaving much of the interpretation to the 
reader she has been compared to such contemporary writers as ann 
beattie and raymond carver who have been called minimalists 
while mason admires carver and beattie she rejects the idea of 
consciously emulating them 
one doesnt like to identify with labels that means that you 
agree that youre part of a movement she said thats just me 
i think in a certain decade lots of people are going to sound 
similar 
describing lilas thoughts the night before her operation mason 
uses short almost telegraphic sentences 
lila cant sleep random scenes pass before her eyes the 
strong comfortable smells of cows in the barn waiting to be 
milked the steamy air in winter gathering in tomatoes before a 
frost sprinkling lime on the potatoes spread out on the ground in 
a stall of the barn laying the onions on screendoor racks above 
mason notes that the real meaning of her stories can be learned 
from the pacing of her writing rather than the words themselves 
hardly anybody points out those things the sentence rhythms 
mean everything because they create the tone and the voice and the 
characters 
for spence lila mason sought to create a delicate mood 
i wanted it be very calm and reflective and tender and deep 
to go way inside its a love story thats why she put a plus 
symbol in the title 
after lilas surgery she and spence return to the farm the 
books ends with this passage in the garden of spence observing lila 
the way she laughs is the moment he has been waiting for she 
rears her head back and laughs steadily her throat working and her 
eyes flashing her throat catches her finally and slows her down 
but her face dances like pond water in the rain all unsettled and 
stirring with aroused possibility 
somebody said to me that the word possibility is the key 
mason said of the ending possibility is what there is 
