<TEXT>
richard pressingers troubles began when 
he was teaching in a portable classroom built with particle board 
his chest hurt he couldnt concentrate and he was depressed he 
had frequent colds and an abnormally low whiteblood cell count 
indicating liver malfunction doctors couldnt determine a cause 
for his symptoms 
pressingers suffering became so intense he finally left his 
girlfriend and gave up his job he joined the peace corps and went 
to teach in jamaica but had to leave after a year because the 
ministry of education began using a strong pesticide in the 
classrooms in which he taught 
suspecting sensitivity to chemicals he began sleeping on a 
beach to escape the smells of pesticides disinfectants paint and 
even perfume 
pressinger 33 is one of a growing number of people who believe 
they are severely allergic to chemicals victims of environmental 
illness 
doctors however cant agree on what is causing symptoms that 
have led some sufferers to seek a toxic free environment by 
giving up their jobs and moving to the desert or even going so far 
as to seal their rooms with aluminum foil linings 
much of what is attributed to environmental factors can only 
be theorized says dr phillip lieberman a memphis tenn 
clinical allergist and president of the american academy of allergy 
and immunology so there is great controversy as to whether the 
precepts of the physicians practicing environmental medicine are 
valid at this time 
the burden of proof belongs on the physicians practicing the 
specialty lieberman says 
dr william rae a cardiovascular surgeon who also specializes 
in clinical ecology says nothing is 100 percent proven but 
most of the debate occurs out of ignorance its a scapegoat for 
not looking into it critically 
rae contends that 10 percent to 20 percent of the population 
suffers from such sensitivity his clinic in dallas says it has 
treated 17000 people for environmental illness in the past dozen 
years 
some of them are sensitive to formaldehyde in particle board 
paneling and rugs others to food or gasoline even the smell of 
deodorant vehicle exhaust newsprint clothes bedding and other 
everyday substances can cause reactions 
pressinger lives at his mothers home here doing everything he 
can to avoid contact with chemicals he believes his only real 
escape is a secluded uninhabited island he has checked out 
properties in florida north carolina and tennessee and now is 
trying to get enough sufferers together to buy an island in the 
bahamas which is untainted by pollution 
the island hes found is 2 miles long and a halfmile wide 
about 5 miles from abaco island its asking price is 4 million and 
pressinger says it could be subdivided for sale just to sufferers 
of chemically caused illnesses 
this type of arrangement would allow complete control of the 
surroundings without the risk of unexpected chemical exposures 
weve got to find someplace its not a matter of if but when 
fred nelson who heads the national foundation for the 
chemically hypersensitive in wrightsville beach nc says the 
group is interested in a chemicalfree environment we feel the 
need is for an inexpensive longterm rehabilitation oasis for the 
environmentally ill and their families 
pressinger also has taken his idea to the chicagobased human 
ecology action league which publishes a magazine runs educational 
campaigns about the problem and helps sufferers find treatment rae 
is one of its directors 
in the beginning i thought i was the only one that had such 
problems says pressinger the initial reaction of doctors is 
that its a psychological problem its a complex illness that is 
little understood even by physicians 
there are many people out there who have it and dont even 
know it 
