<TEXT>
china on monday enacted a law that ends direct 
state controls over enterprises and gives factory managers greater 
freedom over their operations 
the introduction of the enterprise law came with warnings that 
factories will no longer be able to live off state largess and will 
face bankruptcy if they fail to respond to market competition 
the law passed by the national peoples congress last april 
gives factory managers greater autonomy over planning and personnel 
and makes them responsible for profits and losses 
it is to be followed in november by enactment of chinas first 
bankruptcy law which will set down rules for shutting down 
insolvent plants 
legalization of the manager responsibility system already 
widely practiced in chinas staterun factories has been hailed as 
a major step in the governments drive to reduce the role of 
central planning and make industry more efficient by linking its 
production to marketdetermined supply and demand factors 
zhang yanning deputy minister of the state commission for 
restructuring the economy said last week government departments 
that previously exercised direct control over industries should 
abide by the principle of the state regulates the market which 
in turn guides the enterprises 
several years of experimenting with the manager responsibility 
system however has proved the difficulty of following that 
principle 
factory managers are still at the mercy of state allocations 
departments that control disbursement of scarce and increasingly 
expensive energy and raw materials managers told they now must 
make profits are also thwarted by irrationally low stateset 
purchasing prices for many of their products 
approximately onefourth of chinas staterun enterprises are 
operating in the red and the number is increasing with recent 
sharp increases in the costs of raw materials 
the peoples daily the official voice of the communist party 
said in a frontpage commentary monday that chinas 10yearold 
economic structural reforms have entered a critical stage 
enterprises can no longer harbor the illusion that the state 
will provide lowpriced raw materials and subsidies to cover 
losses it said banks will not be a certain source of lowinterest 
loans 
factories must move aggressively to reform their management 
personnel organization and income distribution systems because in 
the future market competition will be relentless 
there will certainly be some enterprises that will fail in the 
competition and be declared bankrupt the newspaper said 
under the new law enterprises will have the right to sell 
products on their own after meeting obligations to the state and 
to choose their own suppliers set product prices and negotiate and 
sign contracts with foreign parties 
senior leader deng xiaoping the mastermind of chinas economic 
reforms first suggested an enterprise law in 1978 but it was not 
until this year that disagreements over the relationship among the 
state the manager and workers were finally worked out 
</TEXT>
