<TEXT>
the us governments exportimport bank 
announced on monday that its board of directors has agreed to 
resume lending to brazil to encourage sales of us goods there 
the action follows an agreement reached in paris over the 
weekend between brazil and 13 creditor governments including the 
united states this accord will delay repayments on 5 billion 
worth of debt falling due between jan 1 1987 and march 31 1990 
sergio amaral head of the brazilian delegation said that none 
of the interest or principal will be repaid until the end of that 
period payments will then be spread over 10 years it is unusual 
for such arrangements to delay payments of both interest and 
principal 
the us bank announced on july 11 that it was accepting 
applications for loans to brazil and that a decision would be made 
after the paris talks 
this condition has been satisfied and eximbank now is prepared 
to act on preliminary and final commitments said the banks 
president john a bohn jr in a statement 
brazils international credit was badly hurt in february 1987 
when it stopped paying interest on more than 60 billion of its 
bank debt the biggest in the third world it now has an agreement 
with a committee representing its bank creditors to delay payments 
on about 62 billion and to take new loans of 52 billion from 
the banks to help pay them the back interest 
the committee is collecting approvals from over 600 creditor 
banks for this arrangement the international monetary fund owned 
by 151 governments has said it will also lend brazil more money 
when the banks have agreed 
</TEXT>
