<TEXT>
soybean corn and oat futures skyrocketed their 
permitted daily limits monday on the chicago board of trade amid 
fears that a new heat wave in the midwest will do further damage to 
droughtstressed crops 
wheat futures also closed sharply higher 
the return of hot dry weather to the corn belt after a twoweek 
reprieve holds a particular threat to the soybean crop which is in 
the middle of its critical podfilling stage analysts said 
high temperatures 95 degrees or higher are more detrimental 
to soybeans at this growth stage than lack of moisture said rich 
feltes director of commodity research with refco inc a large 
chicagobased commodities brokerage house 
temperatures soared into the upper 90s monday afternoon in the 
central corn belt states of iowa illinois missouri and wisconsin 
and the hot dry weather was expected to persist for most of the 
week 
if these high temperatures continue were looking at a 
potentially serious shortfall in soybean production even with the 
recent rains in the eastern corn belt feltes said 
most contracts for future delivery of oats corn and soybeans 
closed up their respective daily limits of 10 cents 15 cents and 
45 cents a bushel the august soybean contract on which the limit 
has been removed pending the contracts expiration later this 
month closed more than 60 cents higher 
at the close wheat was 9 cents to 15 cents higher with 
september at 381 a bushel corn was 13 cents to 15 cents higher 
with september at 290 a bushel oats were 10 cents higher across 
the board with september at 281 a bushel soybeans were 28 
cents to 64 cents higher with august at 840 a bushel 
